properties.description: The eastern Mentelle Basin is the shallower part of the Mentelle Basin comprising lower Permian to Mid-Jurassic interlinked depocentres some of which contain up to 9 km of sediments.
properties.overview: The eastern Mentelle Basin extends across the continental slope in water depths of 500 to 2000 m. It contains five individual depocentres: Baranup, Alexandra, Quindalup, Augusta and Manjimup. It consists of a series of tilted fault blocks that are bounded by east-dipping faults which predominantly strike NNW to NNE. The eastern Mentelle Basin contains inferred Lower Permian and Triassic to Mid-Jurassic syn-rift and thermal subsidence succession. The age control is provided by a seismic tie to two dredges in the Perth Canyon. The pre-breakup succession is likely to contain lower Permian glacio-marine, fluvial, lacustrine and deltaic sediments equivalent to the Mosswood Formation, Woodynook Sandstone and Rosabrook and Redgate coal measures, Triassic Sabina and Lesueur sandstone and lower Jurassic Cattamarra Coal Measures. These units were extensively deformed, faulted and eroded at the onset of Middle Jurassic rifting. The Middle Jurassic to Early Cretaceous succession is largely absent over the eastern Mentelle Basin. Probable source rocks include Permian and lower Jurassic coals and carbonaceous shales. Potentially good reservoirs may exist in fluvial sediments within the pre-breakup succession and also in marine sandstones within the post-breakup succession. The majority of seals within the pre-breakup succession are probably intraformational. Petroleum systems modelling suggests that generation and expulsion probably occurred from the Early to Middle Jurassic onwards. Play types in the eastern Mentelle Basin include: Permian to Early Jurassic faulted anticlines, fault blocks and subunconformity plays as well as stratigraphic pinchout and onlap plays.
properties.source: Borissova, I., Bradshaw, B.E., Nicholson, C.J., Struckmeyer, H.I.M., Payne, D.S., 2010. New exploration opportunities on the southwest Australian margin - deep-water frontier Mentelle Basin, APPEA Journal 50

properties.description: The ?Ordovician to Recent Exmouth sub-basin is one of the main depocentres of the Northern Carnarvon Basin and contains over 12km of predominantly siliciclastics marine and nonmarine sediments
properties.overview: The mostly offshore, ?Ordovician to Recent Exmouth Sub-basin is the southernmost part of the Northern Carnarvon Basin and contains over 12,000 m of predominantly marine and non-marine siliciclastics. The sub-basin is bounded to the northeast by the Alpha Arch, to the southeast by the Rough Range Fault, and to the south by the Bernier Platform. The Carnarvon Basin originated as an intracratonic fracture basin during Silurian rifting, which later evolved into an interior sag basin during the Devonian and Carboniferous. Carboniferous and Permian sedimentation was influenced by glacial conditions, but the return to warmer climatic conditions allowed deposition of extensive fluvio-deltaic to shallow marine sediments. The pre-rift Triassic succession comprises marine shale overlain by fluvio-deltaic sediments, which were in turn overlain by shallow marine sediments. Subsequent Early Jurassic rifting led to the development of the Exmouth Sub-basin and deposition of a thick Lower to Upper Jurassic succession of marine sediments. Uplift and erosion to the south provided a sediment source for Lower Cretaceous marine sandstones which prograded across the sub-basin. Seafloor spreading to the south limited sediment sourcing, and a subsequent structural inversion caused crestal erosion along highs and provided a source for another succession of marine sandstones. A major marine transgression in the Hauterivian marked the beginning of the post-rift phase with deposition of extensive marine shales through most of the Cretaceous, although these are thin in the southern part of the sub-basin. Late Cretaceous to Neogene sedimentation occurred under stable passive margin conditions with extensive deposition of marine carbonates. Since exploration commenced in 1947, 16 hydrocarbon accumulations (oil and gas) have been discovered (Dec 2001). Sandstones of the Lower Cretaceous Barrow Group are the primary reservoirs in the sub-basin. The main play types include faulted anticlines, tilted fault blocks and stratigraphic pinch-outs, with regional seal formed by Lower to Upper Cretaceous marine shales and siltstones. Upper Jurassic marine shales form the principal hydrocarbon source.
properties.source: Tindale, K., Newell, N., Keall, J., Smith, N., 1998. Structural evolution and charge history of the Exmouth Sub-basin, northern Carnarvon Basin, Western Australia, in Purcell, P.G. & Purcell, R.R. (eds), The sedimentary basins of Western Australia 2. Pr*

properties.description: The Permian to Cainozoic Sahul Platform, an element of the northern Bonaparte Basin, contains in excess of 5 km of siliciclastic and carbonate rocks.
properties.overview: The Permian to Cainozoic Sahul Platform is a structural element of the Bonaparte Basin located offshore on Australia's northwestern margin in water depths of 50 to 1500 m. Much of the Sahul Platform falls within the Joint Petroleum Development Area between Australia and East Timor. The Sahul Platform is an area of relatively shallow basement, with sediment thickness varying from 3 km on the Troubadour High to more than 5 km on the Kelp High. The Sahul Platform was originally part of a broad, northeast to southwest trending Late Palaeozoic sag basin. Following Early Jurassic rifting, the platform became a depocentre for non-marine and marginal to shallow marine clastics in the Early to Middle Jurassic. Subsequent break-up in the Callovian produced a series of narrow confined depocentres, the Malita Graben and Sahul Syncline, to the south and west of the elevated Sahul Platform. Upper Jurassic and Lower Cretaceous strata are mainly confined to these depocentres, and are either absent or consist of thin condensed marine mudstones across the Sahul Platform. Late Miocene to Pliocene convergence of the Australian and Eurasian plates resulted in flexural downwarp of the Timor Trough to the north, and generation of the Kelp High and Troubadour High faulted anticline structures. Upper Cretaceous to Tertiary strata consist predominantly of marine carbonates. Exploration is sub-mature with 21 wells drilled by the end of 2002. Discoveries include the giant Sunrise-Troubadour gas-condensate field, and a gas accumulation at Chuditch. Middle Jurassic strata are of greatest economic significance containing the main reservoir and source rock intervals. There is also limited reservoir potential in Permian to Triassic strata. Upper Jurassic and Cretaceous mudstones form the regional seal. The main exploration targets are complex faulted anticlines with hydrocarbons trapped at the apex of large regional structural closure. To date, the Troubadour High in the northeastern part of the Sahul Platfrom has proved to be the most viable exploration area.
properties.source: Labutis, V.R., Ruddock, Calcraft, A.P., 1998. Stratigraphy of the southern Sahul Platform, APPEA Journal 38(1)

properties.description: The Calder Graben is a Mesozoic and Cainozoic depocentre of the Bonaparte Basin in offshore northern Australia. The graben is likely to contain more than 10 km of siliciclastic non-marine and marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Calder Graben is the northeastern part of an elongated, northeast-trending graben system subdivided into the Malita and Calder grabens. These grabens lie between extensive platform and shelf areas of relatively shallow Precambrian basement covered by thin Mesozoic and Cainozoic sediments and in some areas by thin late Palaeozoic sediments. The Calder Graben is a depositional trough, bordered by Troubadour Terrace of the Sahul Platform to the west and the Arafura and Money Shoal basins to the east. It is bounded on both sides by northeast-trending faults with large displacements. The graben system was initiated during Early Jurassic rifting and was a major depocentre during the Middle and Late Jurassic, and the Early Cretaceous. Total sediment thickness of the graben is unknown. However, the graben system is likely to contain a late Palaeozoic to Recent sedimentary succession, exceeding perhaps 10 km in total thickness. Open-file data relating to sediment type, age and environment of deposition are very sparse in this region. Only a regional stratigraphic interpretation can be made from the limited open-file data available. The Abadi gas accumulation is the geographically nearest hydrocarbon discovery, which is located north in Indonesian waters. However, this discovery is probably situated on a northeastern extension of the Sahul Platform. In the Calder Graben, both potential source rocks and potential reservoir rocks occur in Jurassic, Cretaceous and Tertiary sediments. In general, claystone dominates the Jurassic and Cretaceous intervals, but its source rock quality is usually low. The Lynedoch horst is the largest structural feature in the graben. After drilling two wells on the structure, the reservoir potential of Middle Jurassic sandstones has been downgraded. Tertiary sandstones in unfaulted subtle structural features could be potential reservoir targets in the graben.
properties.source: West, B., Passmore, V.L., 1994. Hydrocarbon potential for the Bathurst Island Group, Northeast Bonaparte Basin: implication for future exploration., APEA Journal 34(1)

properties.description: The Scott Plateau is a subsided plateau on the outboard margin of the Browse Basin. It is characterised by widespread igneous rocks and is interpreted to contain a Paleozoic-Cenozoic succession.
properties.overview: The southern part of the deep-water Browse region is dominated by the under explored Carboniferous-Holocene Scott Plateau in modern day water depths of 1700->5000 m. The Scott Plateau contains a thick (>5 km) section of Paleozoic-Mesozoic rocks. Across much of the Scott Plateau, a thin Jurassic(?) to Cenozoic sedimentary section overlies a thick and extensive succession of igneous rocks that to a large extent obscures the underlying geology on seismic data. The northeastern Scott Plateau consists of a broad platform characterised by rotated, planar normal faults. This region is flanked to the west by the Wilson Spur, a 50 km wide elevated feature on the edge of the Scott Plateau, and to the east by the Seringapatam Sub-basin. The Scott Plateau appears to have undergone extreme crustal thinning during the Early-Middle Jurassic. Breakup and the initiation of seafloor spreading in the Argo Abyssal Plain to the west of the Scott Plateau occurred in the Callovian and were accompanied by volcanism and igneous intrusions, and widespread erosion. The petroleum potential of the Scott Plateau has not been tested. The lack of wells and high quality seismic data limits understanding of the geology and petroleum prospectivity of the region.
properties.source: Hoffman, N., Hill, K.C., 2004. Structural-stratigraphic evolution and hydrocarbon prospectivity of the deep-water Browse Basin, North West Shelf, Australia. In: Ellis, G.K., Baillie, P.W. & Munson, T.J. (Editors), Timor Sea Petroleum Geoscience. Proceed*

properties.description: The Permian to Cainozoic Troubadour Terrace is a tectonic element of the Bonaparte Basin and contains more than 5 km of siliciclastic and carbonate rocks with no commercial reserves of hydrocarbons.
properties.overview: The Troubadour Terrace is a structural element of the Bonaparte Basin located offshore on Australia's northwestern margin in water depths of 50 to 1500 m. It forms part of the same structural feature as the Sahul Platform, and is only arbitrarily separated from it. The Sahul Platform and Troubadour Terrace are an area of relatively shallow basement, with fairly uniform sediment thickness varying from 3 km to more than 5 km. The Sahul Platform and Troubadour Terrace were originally part of a broad, northeast to southwest trending late Palaeozoic sag basin. Following Early Jurassic rifting, the area became a depocentre for non-marine and marginal to shallow marine clastics in the Early to Middle Jurassic. Subsequent break-up in the Callovian produced a series of narrow confined depocentres in the eastern Bonaparte Basin. Upper Jurassic and Lower Cretaceous strata are mainly confined to these depocentres, and are either absent or consist of thin condensed marine mudstones across the Sahul Platform and Troubadour Terrace. Late Miocene to Pliocene convergence of the Australian and Eurasian plates resulted in generation of highly faulted anticline structures. Upper Cretaceous to Tertiary strata consist predominantly of marine carbonates. Exploration on the Troubadour Terrace is sub-mature with 4 wells drilled by 2000, resulting in the discovery of the Evans Shoal gas accumulation. The Abadi gas accumulation is likely on the northeastern extension of the Sahul Platform and Troubadour Terrace. The Middle Jurassic Plover Formation is of greatest economic significance containing the main reservoir and source rock intervals. Upper Jurassic and Cretaceous mudstones form the regional seal. The main exploration targets are complex faulted anticlines.
properties.source: Labutis, V.R., Ruddock, Calcraft, A.P., 1998. Stratigraphy of the southern Sahul Platform, APPEA Journal 38(1)

properties.description: The ?Late Cambrian to Tertiary Gascoyne Sub-basin (Southern Carnarvon Basin) is an onshore/offshore depocentre on the west Australian coast, containing up to 5km of marine and non-marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Gascoyne Sub-basin is an onshore/offshore sub-division of the Southern Carnarvon Basin in Western Australia. Only ten exploration wells have been drilled in the Gascoyne Sub-basin (March 2003). Minor oil and gas shows were encountered in Silurian and Devonian strata from several wells. The sub-basin is a structurally elevated platform adjacent to the eastern Permian and Mesozoic depocentres of the Southern Carnarvon Basin. The Gascoyne Sub-basin comprises two distinct depocentres containing up to 5km of ?Cambrian to Devonian strata overlain by a thin Cretaceous to Cainozoic cover. Sedimentation in the Gascoyne Sub-basin commenced with widespread fluvial deposition, followed by uplift and erosion. A period of faulting during the Ordovician was associated with deposition of fluvial and coastal redbeds. This was followed by deposition of marine-restricted carbonates and evaporites during the Silurian, mixed siliciclastics and dolomite in a shallow marine environment during the Early Devonian, and shallow marine to coastal siliciclastics and shelf carbonates during the Middle Devonian to mid Carboniferous. Collision of Gondwana and Laurasia initiated a period of uplift and subsequent erosion during the mid-Carboniferous. Evidence for sedimentation in the Gascoyne Sub-basin during the Permian to Triassic is limited, suggesting the basin was a topographically high feature at this time. Faulting associated with the Early Cretaceous break-up of Australia and Greater India overprinted older structures. A Miocene compression event caused reverse movement on many faults. The main known source rocks in the Gascoyne Sub-basin are Silurian- and Devonian- age, organic rich and oil-prone laminated mudstones within carbonate facies. Peak hydrocarbon expulsion from these sources was during the Late Permian to Middle Jurassic. The main exploration target has been Lower Cretaceous sandstones sealed by marine shales within Miocene anticlinal structures. Palaeozoic targets also exist, including fault traps which contain Ordovician reservoirs sealed by Triassic marine shales, and Devonian reefal carbonates with intraformational seals.
properties.source: Iasky, R.P., D'Ercole, C., Ghori, K.A.R., Mory, A.J., Lockwood, A.M., 2003. Structure and petroleum prospectivity of the Gascoyne Platform, Western Australia., Geological Survey of Western Australia. Report 87

properties.description: The Palaeozoic to Recent Northern Carnarvon Basin, Australia's premier hydrocarbon province, lies mainly offshore on the multiple-rifted northwest Australian margin, and contains up to 15 km of Mesozoic clastic deltaic and marine sediments.
properties.overview: The Palaeozoic to Recent Northern Carnarvon Basin, is a large, mainly offshore basin on Australia's northwest shelf. It is Australia's premier hydrocarbon province where the majority of deepwater wells (greater than 500 m water depth) have been drilled. Since exploration drilling commenced in 1953, 754 exploration wells have been drilled (Dec 2001) and 145 GL of oil, 52 GL of condensate and 207 BCM of gas have been produced. The major basin faults trend north or northeast and define a series of structural highs and sub-basins that contain abundant mature source rocks. The basin developed during four successive periods of extension and thermal subsidence. The first phase, Silurian to Permian, developed as a series of intracratonic basins during the breakup of Gondwana along the western margin of Australia. Subsequent Early Jurassic extension initiated four main depocentres; the Exmouth, Barrow, Dampier and Beagle sub-basins. A third extension phase in the Middle Jurassic resulted in seafloor spreading in the Argo Abyssal Plain to the north, and the fourth Tithonian to Valanginian rifting phase culminated in the creation of the Gascoyne-Cuvier abyssal plains to the west and south. The extensive deep-water (800 to 5000 m) Exmouth Plateau forms a bathymetric Plateau outboard of the main depocentres, and developed in response to thermal sag after Valanginian breakup. The depocentres contain up to 15 km of sedimentary section. Triassic to Lower Cretaceous strata are dominantly siliciclastic deltaic to marine deposits, whereas slope and shelfal marls and carbonates dominate the Mid Cretaceous to Cainozoic section. These carbonates were deposited as a series of northwestward prograding wedges as the region continued to cool and subside. This resulted in deep burial of the underlying Mesozoic source and reservoir sequences in the depocentres. Most of the basin's hydrocarbon resources are reservoired within Upper Triassic, Jurassic and Lower Cretaceous sandstones beneath the regional Cretaceous seal.
properties.source: Hocking, R.M., 1988. Regional geology of the northern Carnarvon Basin. IN Purcell P.G. and Purcell R.R. eds - The North West Shelf, Australia., Petroleum Exploration Society of Australia 1v

properties.description: The ultra-deep water western Mentelle Basin contains Mid-Jurassic to early Cretaceous syn-rift and early Cretaceous to Holocene post-rift successions separated by a thick Valanginian to Hauterivian syn-breakup igneous complex.
properties.overview: The western Mentelle Basin is an ultra-deep water part of the Mentelle Basin containing up to 11 km of sedimentary fill. The two major depocentres of the western Mentelle Basin, Eagle and Rosa, were formed during Mid-Jurassic to Early Cretaceous rifting. Half graben within the western Mentelle Basin are bounded by easterly dipping faults in the Eagle depocentre and southeasterly dipping faults in the Rosa depocentre. Paleocene to Eocene margin collapse associated with the onset of the fast spreading in the Southern Ocean resulted in fault reactivation and inversion. The stratigraphy of the western Mentelle Basin is inferred from seismic ties to DSDP 258, which provides high resolution data on Mid-Albian to Holocene part of the section, and comparisons to the adjacent Vlaming Sub-basin. Petroleum prospectivity assessment based on well data from the Perth Basin suggests that potential source rocks include Middle Jurassic to early Cretaceous coals and carbonaceous shales. Good quality reservoir rocks are likely to be present at multiple stratigraphic levels. Regional seals are likely to be associated with breakup-related volcanics and Albian marine mudstones. Petroleum systems modelling suggests that only Jurassic rocks have reached the oil window. Generation and expulsion from these source rocks probably occurred from the Early Cretaceous onwards. Play types in the western Mentelle Basin include syn-rift high-side fault block traps, sub-basalt anticlines and fault blocks, post-rift anticlines and a range of stratigraphic traps.
properties.source: Borissova, I., Bradshaw, B.E., Nicholson, C.J., Struckmeyer, H.I.M., Payne, D.S., 2010. New exploration opportunities on the southwest Australian margin - deep-water frontier Mentelle Basin, APPEA Journal 50

properties.description: The Palaeozoic to Recent Rankin Platform is located in the Northern Carnarvon Basin and contains up to 12km of fluvial, deltaic and marine sediments. It is a mature offshore hydrocarbon province with numerous oil and gas discoveries.
properties.overview: The Palaeozoic to Recent Rankin Platform is a prominent northeast-trending structural high in the Northern Carnarvon Basin, consisting of a series of tilted fault blocks, formed in response to the final stages of the break-up of eastern Gondwana. The Rankin Platform consists of approximately 12 km of sediments (based on seismic cross-section) ranging in age from the Palaeozoic to Recent, with a very thin or absent Jurassic section. Pre-rift sequences (Triassic to mid-Pleinsbachian) are composed of marine and fluvio-deltaic sediments. The syn-rift phase (mid-Pliensbachian to mid-Valanginian), during which the platform structure formed, is composed of deltaic to restricted marine sediments. The post-rift (mid Valanginian to mid-Santonian) to passive margin phase (mid-Santonian to Miocene) is composed of transgressive shaly marine sediments to a variety of marine carbonate sediments deposited in open marine shelfal environments. The current day water depths reach a maximum of approximately 500m. The Rankin Platform is a proven hydrocarbon province, with many large gas and condensate accumulations and several oil fields. In the Dampier/Rankin region there were a total of 49 field discoveries and 120 exploration wells with a technical success rate of 41% at the end of 2001. The majority of gas is contained in Upper Triassic (Mungaroo Formation) to Lower Jurassic reservoirs in tilted horsts on the Rankin Platform. The reservoirs are sealed by the Lower Cretaceous Muderong Shale or Upper Jurassic Dingo Claystone. Gaseous hydrocarbons on the Rankin Platform are sourced from the Triassic. Oils on the eastern inshore part of the Rankin Platform are derived from source rocks within the marine Dingo Claystone of the Dampier Sub-basin. Maturity calculations suggest that hydrocarbon generation from Triassic source rocks commenced in the Jurassic. However, the fact that large quantities of gaseous hydrocarbons have been discovered on the Rankin Platform suggests that the major phase of gas generation and migration post-dated the deposition of the Cretaceous seal.
properties.source: Vincent, P., Tilbury, L., 1988. Gas and oil fields of the Rankin Trend and the northern Barrow-Dampier Sub-basin., In: Purcell P.G., Purcell, R.R. (editors),  The North West Shelf. Proceedings of the Northwest Shelf Symposium, PESA, Perth, WA

properties.description: The Exmouth Plateau is a large, mid-slope, continental margin plateau underlain by a thick, generally flat-lying Carboniferous to Recent section . The main phases of sedimentation were related to Palaeozoic thermal subsidence and Mesozoic rifting and breakup that took place along the length of the northwestern margin of Australia.
properties.overview: The Exmouth Plateau is a large, mid-slope continental margin plateau lying at water depths of 800 m to more than 3000 m off northwest Australia. It is a major structural element of the Northern Carnarvon Basin, the southernmost component of the late Palaeozoic to Cainozoic Westralian Superbasin.  To the southeast, the plateau is bounded by the high-standing Rankin Platform and the Exmouth Sub-basin of the Northern Carnarvon Basin.  To the north, the plateau is abutted by Late Jurassic oceanic crust of the Argo Abyssal Plain, while to the northwest and southwest the plateau abuts the Valanginian and younger oceanic crust of the Gascoyne and Cuvier Abyssal Plains.  The margins of the plateau, in particular, are strongly affected by volcanics related to the two episodes of continental breakup. Most of the Exmouth Plateau is underlain by 1015 km of generally flat-lying, faulted sedimentary section, largely deposited during a Permo-Carboniferous sag phase and the TriassicJurassic rift phase that preceded the Middle Jurassic breakup of Argo Land and Australia.  Jurassic sediments are thin or absent, except beneath the northern margin of the plateau; faulted fluvio-deltaic Triassic sediments are generally overlain by sediments of the northwards-prograding Barrow Group delta.  Since the Early Cretaceous breakup of Greater India and Australia, the Exmouth Plateau region has largely been sediment-starved, and only a few hundred metres of mid-Cretaceous to Cainozoic marine sediments are present.  During this period, the area has been subject to several episodes of structural re-activation that have influenced hydrocarbon migration and entrapment. Sandstones of the Upper Triassic Mungaroo Formation and the Lower Cretaceous Barrow Group have been the major exploration objectives on the Exmouth Plateau. The economic importance of Jurassic reservoirs had been overlooked until the early 2000s when a series of Jurassic discoveries were made. To date, all discoveries on the plateau have comprised dry gas.
properties.source: Stagg, H.M.J., Colwell, J.B., 1994. The structural foundations of the Northern Carnarvon Basin, in Purcell, P.G. & Purcell, R.R. (eds), The sedimentary basins of Western Australia. Proceedings of a PESA Symposium, Perth

properties.description: The Mentelle Basin is a large offshore frontier basin located on the southwest Australian margin, containing up to 11 km of fluvio-lacustrine, deltaic and marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Mentelle Basin is a large offshore basin located on the southwest Australian continental margin. It is a deep to extremely deep-water (500 to 4000 m) frontier basin with limited previous petroleum exploration. The Mentelle Basin formed through several phases of extension: the early Permian, early Jurassic and Middle Jurassic to Early Cretaceous. During the last extensional episode it was located near a triple junction between Australia, Antarctica and India and its southern part has structural elements consistent with extensional directions on the southern margin. The Mentelle Basin is divided into the two key structural domains, the western and the eastern Mentelle basins, with different fault and depocentre geometries. The bulk of the sedimentary fill in the eastern Mentelle Basin depocentres is interpreted to be a lower Permian to Jurassic pre-breakup succession (up to 7 km) overlain by a thin post-breakup succession. In the western Mentelle Basin the sedimentary fill is interpreted to be a mid-Jurassic to Early Cretaceous pre-breakup succession (up to 9 km) overlain by a thick post-breakup succession (up to 2.5 km). The Valanginian breakup was accompanied by extensive volcanism. An igneous unit extends throughout the western Mentelle Basin and is up to 1 km thick. Current petroleum prospectivity assessment is based on correlations to age-equivalent units in the Vlaming Sub-basin. This correlation suggests that the basin contains multiple source rock intervals and good quality reservoir rocks and seals. Petroleum systems modelling indicates that generation and expulsion from potential source rocks commenced in the early Cretaceous and continued throughout the Cenozoic. The Mentelle Basin offers a wide range of play types including faulted anticlines and high-side fault blocks, sub-basalt anticlines and fault blocks, and a large range of stratigraphic and unconformity plays. Direct hydrocarbon indicators in the Mentelle Basin include seismic amplitude anomalies and significant SAR anomalies.
properties.source: Borissova, I., Bradshaw, B.E., Nicholson, C.J., Struckmeyer, H.I.M., Payne, D.S., 2010. New exploration opportunities on the southwest Australian margin - deep-water frontier Mentelle Basin, APPEA Journal 50

properties.description: The Seringapatam Sub-basin is the northernmost  portion of the deepwater Browse Basin and contains a thick pre- and syn-rift Paleozoic-Upper Jurassic sucession and a thin post-rift Jurassic-Cenozoic sucession.
properties.overview: The northernmost element of the deep-water Browse Basin is the underexplored Seringapatam Sub-basin in modern day water depths of 1050-2200 m. It contains a faulted, pre- to syn-breakup, Paleozoic(?) to Upper Jurassic section up to 4 s TWT thick, overlain by a thin Upper Jurassic-Cenozoic post-breakup succession. The basin fill is characterised by extensive intrusive and extrusive igneous rocks. Deposition of Lower-Middle Jurassic sediments extended into the deepwater depocentres of the Seringapatam Sub-basin, forming a depositional wedge that thins onto the Scott Plateau. In the Middle-Late Jurassic, extension became localised in the eastern Seringapatam Sub-basin. Deposition failed to keep pace with subsidence, forming a sediment trap outboard of the Caswell Sub-basin. Post-Jurassic deposition occurred in a distal deepwater setting. During the late Miocene, an increase in subsidence was matched by increased sediment supply resulting in the deposition of a 1 km thick westward thinning sediment wedge. The petroleum potential of the Seringapatam Sub-basin has not been tested. The most prospective section is likely to be the thick but narrow rift depocentre on the eastern side of the sub-basin. Plover Formation may have accumulated during the pre- and early-rift stages, while thick syn- to immediately post-rift sequences (Vulcan Formation) may have been deposited in the Late Jurassic. If present, Jurassic-early Cretaceous source rocks would be mature for oil and gas generation, but with variable expulsion potential. Reservoir and seal facies distributions are largely unknown. Triassic-Jurassic fault blocks, inversion anticlines and stratigraphic plays in the submarine fans of the Echuca Shoals and Puffin formations may be potential plays.
properties.source: Hoffman, N., Hill, K.C., 2004. Structural-stratigraphic evolution and hydrocarbon prospectivity of the deep-water Browse Basin, North West Shelf, Australia. In: Ellis, G.K., Baillie, P.W. & Munson, T.J. (Editors), Timor Sea Petroleum Geoscience. Proceed*

properties.description: The Barcoo Sub-basin is one of two main depocentres of the Holocene to Carboniferous Browse Basin. It contains more than 12 km of siliciclastic non-marine, marine and deltaic rocks.
properties.overview: The Barcoo Sub-basin is a major depocentre of the Browse Basin in the southern Timor Sea region of Australias North West Shelf and contains a Paleozoic to Cenozoic succession up to 12,000 m thick. The Barcoo Sub-basin is separated from the Caswell Sub-basin by the Buffon Scott Reef Brecknock Anticlinal Trend, which hosts the Calliance, Brecknock and Torosa gas fields. The Barcoo Sub-basin was initiated in the Carboniferous-early Permian in response to north-northwest-oriented extension. Contractional reactivation in the Late Triassic was followed by further extension and volcanism during the Early-Middle Jurassic, which culminated in continental breakup. Post-breakup passive margin subsidence was interrupted by a Miocene inversion event associated with the Australian-Eurasian collisional event that resulted in the formation of large inversion anticlines along the southeastern boundary of the sub-basin. Initial Late Carboniferous-early Permian fluvio-deltaic deposition was followed by dominantly marine conditions in the early Permian-Triassic. Late Triassic inversion was marked by the formation of large NE-trending anticlines and the deposition of a syn-inversion succession. Early to Middle Jurassic syn-rift deposition was dominated by the fluvio-deltaic Plover Formation. Intrusive and extrusive igneous rocks are common within the Jurassic succession. Post-breakup Upper Jurassic-Paleogene deposition was dominated by deltaic to marine conditions, with clastic dominated deposition succeeded in the Oligocene by the accumulation of progradational carbonate facies. Potential source rocks in the Barcoo Sub-basin include the oil and gas mature Plover Formation, and marginally mature-immature Upper Jurassic-Lower Cretaceous shales (Vulcan and Echuca Shoals formations). Equivalents of the Permo-Triassic Kinmore Group may provide an additional source in less deeply buried areas. The Plover and Montara formations provide the main reservoir target in the Barcoo Sub-basin, and regional seal is provided by shales of the Echuca Shoals and Vulcan formations.
properties.source: Kennard, J.M., Deighton, I., Ryan, D., Edwards, D.S., Boreham, C.J., 2004. Subsidence and thermal history modelling: new insights into hydrocarbon expulsion from multiple petroleum systems in the Browse Basin. In: Ellis, G.K., Baillie, P.W. and Munson, *

properties.description: The Rowley Sub-basin is located on Australia's North West Shelf in the northern Roebuck Basin. It contains a Late Paleozoic-Cenozoic succession in excess of 8 km thick.
properties.overview: The Rowley Sub-basin comprises the northern two-thirds of the Roebuck Basin, covering an area of approximately 64,000 square kilometres. It is flanked to the southwest by the Beagle Sub-basin (Northern Carnarvon Basin) and to the northeast by the Barcoo Sub-basin (Browse Basin). It is separated from the Bedout Sub-basin and the offshore Canning Basin by a structural feature comprising the Bedout and Oobagooma highs. The Rowley Sub-basin contains in excess of 6 km of Paleozoic-Middle Jurassic strata unconformably overlain by up to 2.5 km of Callovian-Holocene sediments. The Paleozoic to Middle Jurassic pre-breakup succession onlaps the Oobagooma High, Broome Platform and Bedout High to the east and southeast. This section forms a seaward-thickening wedge that is terminated at the escarpment defining the continent-ocean boundary. An unconformity at the top of the Paleozoic to Middle Jurassic section is overlain by prograding Callovian-Holocene sequences. The sub-basin forms part of the Westralian Superbasin. Initiation of the Westralian Superbasin in the Late Carboniferous was driven by northwest-southeast extension related to the separation of the Sibumasu terrane from Gondwana. Fault systems within the Rowley Sub-basin reflect this stress regime and generally strike northeast-southwest. Compared with the adjacent Browse and Northern Carnarvon basins, the Rowley Sub-basin is only mildly structured.
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Paleozoic to Cenozoic Flamingo Syncline is a northwest-trending depocentre of the northern Bonaparte Basin. The syncline is part of the Jurassic Elang-Elang Petroleum System.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Permian to Recent Vulcan Sub-basin is a small, offshore, sub-mature depocentre in the Timor Sea, containing up to 10 km of carbonate and siliciclastic marine and non-marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Vulcan Sub-basin is a northeast-trending Mesozoic extensional depocentre in the western Bonaparte Basin, comprising a series of horsts, grabens and terraces. The proto-Vulcan depocentre was probably initiated in the Late Carboniferous to Early Permian as a rift basin. During the Late Permian to Triassic, a thick succession of shallow marine to fluvio-deltaic sediments were deposited, followed by Late Triassic north-south transpression which resulted in uplift and erosion of the region. Fluvio-deltaic clastics were deposited during the Early to Middle Jurassic. The Vulcan Sub-basin rift developed as an intra-continental graben in the late Callovian, and structuring continued through to the Tithonian to form a series of grabens, horsts and terraces. A thick succession of Oxfordian organic-rich marine shales accumulated within the Swan and Paqualin grabens. Post-rift regional thermal subsidence commenced in the Valanginian, after which Upper Cretaceous fine-grained carbonates developed, followed by sub-tropical and tropical carbonates and reefs during the Tertiary. In the Late Miocene to Early Pliocene, convergence of the Australian and Eurasian plates resulted in structural reactivation of many Mesozoic extensional faults. The Vulcan Sub-basin has proven oil and gas potential, with commercial production and sub-commercial discoveries. Proven source rocks include the Vulcan Formation (Late Jurassic), and parts of the Plover (Early-Middle Jurassic) formation. Regional seal is provided by the Lower Cretaceous Echuca Shoal and Jamieson Formation. Reservoir units include the Upper Triassic Challis and Nome formations, middle Jurassic Plover Formation, Callovian to Oxfordian Montara Formation, unnamed Tithonian  sands and the Upper Cretaceous Puffin Formation. Traps include tilted fault blocks and horsts, and lowstand basinfloor fans. It is estimated that the Vulcan Sub-basin contains reserves of 357 MMBBL of oil, 31 MMBBL of Condensate, and  and 1.3 TCF of gas.
properties.source: Pattillo, J., Nicholls, P.J., 1990. A tectonostratigraphic framework for the Vulcan Graben, Timor Sea region., APEA Journal 30(1)

properties.description: The ?Late Cambrian to Recent Southern Carnarvon Basin is a large, mainly onshore basin on the Western Australian poly-phased margin containing up to 7 km of predominantly Palaeozoic siliciclastic and carbonate sedimentary rocks.
properties.comments: Basin contains predominantly ?Cambrian- to Permian-age rocks with a thin Mesozoic and Cainozoic cover.
properties.overview: The Southern Carnarvon Basin is a large, mainly onshore basin on the Western Australian poly-phased margin that incorporates a series of depocentres for Palaeozoic rocks. About 20 exploration wells have been drilled (March 2003), several with minor oil and gas shows. The basin consists of the Gascoyne, Merlinleigh, and Byro sub-basins, and Bernier Platform. The Gascoyne Sub-basin contains up to 5 km of ?Late Cambrian to Devonian strata and a thin Cretaceous to Cainozoic cover. The other sub-basins contain up to 7 km of predominantly Carboniferous to Permian strata with a Mesozoic veneer that thickens to the north and west. The first regional deformation event within the Southern Carnarvon Basin was associated with mid-Carboniferous to Early Permian rifting, which initiated the major depocentres along the eastern margin (Merlinleigh and Byro sub-basins), and was probably associated with uplift and erosion in the Gascoyne Sub-basin. Subsequent deformation events include Late Permian rifting, Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous rifting and break-up, and Miocene inversion. Sedimentation in the Southern Carnarvon Basin began with three redbed-carbonate cycles in the Late Cambrian to Early Devonian. A Middle Devonian break in sedimentation was followed by deposition of marine to coastal siliciclastics and carbonates during the Middle Devonian to Early Carboniferous. Glacial sedimentation dominated during mid-Carboniferous and Early Permian rifting, and was followed by deposition of fluvial-deltaic to marine siliciclastics during the Early to Late Permian. Lower Permian gas-prone source rocks are thick and widespread in the Merlinleigh and Byro sub-basins, and had peak generation/migration during the Triassic. Thin, localised oil-prone source rocks occur within Upper Silurian and Upper Devonian strata in the Gascoyne Sub-basin, and had peak generation/migration during the Permian. Mid-Carboniferous to Early Permian structures are the most prospective, with remigration into younger age structures also possible. Preservation of hydrocarbon accumulations is the main exploration risk.
properties.source: Mory, A.J., Iasky, R.P., Ghori, K.A.R., 2003. A summary of the geological evolution and petroleum potential of the Southern Carnarvon Basin, Western Australia, Geological Survey of Western Australia. Report 86

properties.description: The Peedamullah Shelf is a structural high which forms part of the inboard region of the Northern Carnarvon Basin. It is comprised of Ordovician to Holocene sedimentary rocks. The Flinders Fault System forms the northwestern boundary of the shelf .
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Sahul Syncline is one of a series of a northwest-trending Paleozoic to Cenozoic depocentres in the Bonaparte Basin that link and offset the Vulcan Sub-basin and the Malita and Calder graben rift systems. The synclines are the primary source kitchens for petroleum accumulations on the Laminaria and Flamingo Highs.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The ?Jurassic to Recent Zeewyck Sub-basin is a moderate size, deep water, frontier, strike-slip sub-basin within the Perth Basin containing at least 7 km of ?continental to marine strata.
properties.overview: The Zeewyck Sub-basin  a recently defined structural element of the Perth Basin that describes a north-south to northwest-southeast trending, strike-slip basin that extends over an area of 15,400 sq. km. It is a deep water (1 to 5 km water depth), frontier basin with no previous petroleum exploration. The main depocentre is located just west of the Houtman Sub-basin, and is characterised by a symmetrical, unfaulted sag wedge that overlies and onlaps an extensively faulted sedimentary section, and underlies a basinward-thinning passive margin cover.  The faulted section is believed to contain at least 4 km of Jurassic continental to marine siliciclastics, while the sag fill contains up to 2 km of strata that are possibly equivalent to marine siliciclastics from the Lower Cretaceous Warnbro Group. Overlying passive margin strata are about 1.2 km thick, and are correlated with Aptian to Recent deepwater calcareous and argillaceous rocks from DSDP 259, drilled just west of the Zeewyck Sub-basin. Farther south, the Zeewyck Sub-basin is narrower and shows evidence for localised compressional tectonics with a small fold-thrust belt. The Zeewyck Sub-basin is believed to have been subjected to strike-slip tectonism along the Turtle Dove Transfer either during or just after breakup of the southwest Australian margin and Greater India during the Valanginian. The petroleum potential of the Zeewyck Sub-basin is difficult to evaluate due to the absence of well data to constrain the presence of source rocks. However, the Zeewyck Sub-basin may have generated hydrocarbons from Jurassic and Lower Cretaceous source rock intervals later (post Valanginian) than other source kitchens in the Perth Basin, and have provided a charge to structural and stratigraphic traps within the Zeewyck Sub-basin, and adjoining sub-basins. Some evidence for an active petroleum system in the Zeewyck Sub-basin is provided by SAR anomalies detected just south of the main depocentre.
properties.source: Bradshaw, B.E., Rollet, N., Totterdell, J.M., Borissova, I., 2003. A revised structural framework for frontier basins on the southern and southwestern Australian continental margin., Geoscience Australia. Record 2003/03

properties.description: The Dandaragan Trough is a north-south oriented extensional depocentre in the northern Perth Basin adjacent to the Darling Fault. It contains up to 15,000 m of Permian to Cretaceous sedimentary rocks, overlain by thin Cenozoic sediments.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Paleozoic to Cenozoic Flamingo High, located in the northern Bonaparte Basin, separates the Flamingo and Sahul synclines. The Flamingo High forms part of the Jurassic Elang-Elang Petroleum System, with existing oil and gas fields and reservoirs within the Jurassic Plover and Elang Formations.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Permian to Recent Vasse Shelf is a relatively shallow, narrow, north-south trending structural element that contains up to 3km of predominantly siliciclastic non-marine sedimentary rocks and a substantial, arenaceous, coal-bearing succession.
properties.overview: The Permian to Recent Vasse Shelf is a relatively shallow, narrow, north-south to north-northwest- to south-southeast trending structural element located on the southwestern margin of the Perth Basin. The Vasse Shelf extends over an area of 4500 sq. km and has significant onshore and offshore components (0 to 1000 m water depth). It contains up to 2000 m of Permian sediments which thicken eastward, overlain by a maximum of 1000 m of Mesozoic sediments which thin to the west. The Vasse Shelf is a shallow footwall block that formed against the Leeuwin Complex on the western margin of the main rift basin in the Bunbury Trough and southern Vlaming Sub-basin during Permian to Early Cretaceous rifting. Seismic data from the offshore northern extent of the Vasse Shelf show that it consists of some small west-dipping half graben formed during Permian rifting. Strike-slip faults and contractional duplex structures are also common. Sedimentary rocks deposited in the Vasse Shelf include Lower Permian glaciogenic argillaceous sediments overlain by a substantial arenaceous, coal-bearing, Permian succession deposited in a fluvial to lacustrine deltaic environment, and Triassic fluvial sandstones. Three hydrocarbon exploration wells have been drilled in the Vasse Shelf (Jan 2004), two onshore and one offshore, with no hydrocarbons recovered. The Permian section of the Vasse Shelf contains good reservoir rocks and potential structural traps. However, hydrocarbon migration from adjacent depocentres is required for traps to be charged as the depth of burial for Permian strata on the Vasse Shelf is insufficient for significant hydrocarbon generation. The Permian Sue Group has been explored for its coal mining potential in the northern Vasse Shelf where coal seams are shallow. The Rosabrook Coal Measures has the greatest potential for economic coal resources as they possess the thickest (up to 4.5 m) and highest quality (black, bituminous) seams.
properties.source: Iasky, R.P., 1993. A structural study of the southern Perth basin, Western Australia., Geological Survey of Western Australia. Report 31

properties.description: The Londonderry High is an offshore, Permo-Triassic horst and graben complex. The Londonderry High forms the inboard, southwestern part of the Bonaparte Basin on Australia's northwest continental shelf.
properties.overview: The Londonderry High covers an area of 48610 sq. km and is one of the main basin-forming elements of the Bonaparte Basin on Australia?s northwest continental shelf. The Londonderry High is a Permo-Triassic horst and graben complex which was eroded to produce sediment during Late Jurassic rifting. The Londonderry High borders the Browse Basin in the southwest, the Vulcan Sub-basin in the west, the Nancar Trough and Sahul Syncline in the north, and the Petrel Sub-basin in the east. The maximum sediment thickness on the Londonderry High is in the order of 5000 m. The oldest known rocks are Permian-aged marine units of the Hyland Bay Formation which are conformably overlain by a thick, largely marine Triassic succession of the Sahul Group. The overlying Lower Jurassic Malita Formation comprises red beds. The pre-breakup Jurassic Plover Formation is a sandy, upward-transgressive succession and forms one of the main reservoir targets. The post-breakup, Upper Jurassic-Lower Cretaceous Flamingo Group unconformably overlies the Plover Formation and exhibits good reservoir sandstones near its base. The dominantly fine-grained facies of the Cretaceous Bathurst Island Group unconformably overlie the Flamingo Group and provide the regional seal. The Tertiary Hibernia Formation comprises prograding marine facies separated by an angular unconformity from undifferentiated Miocene and younger carbonates. Over thirty exploration wells were drilled by 2003 on the Londonderry High, with numerous oil shows (fluorescence, cut, live oil, residual oil zones), strong gas shows and several sub-commercial gas discoveries (Promethius-1, Rubicon-1). However, there are no commercial discoveries to date. Most of the wells drilled targeted fault-dependant traps that formed during Mesozoic rifting. Such traps were reactivated during flexural extension associated with plate collision in the Neogene.
properties.source: Brincat, M.P., O'Brien, G.W., Lisk, M., De Ruig, M., George, S.C., 2001. Hydrocarbon charge history of the northern Londonderry High: Implications for trap integrity and future prospectivity., APPEA Journal 41(1)

properties.description: The Nancar Trough is a Late Paleozoic to Cenozoic depocentre in the Bonaparte Basin containing source rocks which are likely to have charged hydrocarbons found on adjacent structural highs. It represents the western extension of the Sahul Syncline, between the Laminaria and Londonderry Highs.
properties.overview: The Nancar Trough is located in the northern Bonaparte Basin, to the northeast of the Vulcan Sub-basin. The Nancar Trough, Sahul Syncline and Flamingo Syncline form a series of a Paleozoic to Cenozoic depocentres that link and offset the Vulcan Sub-basin and the Malita and Calder graben rift systems. These synclines are likely to be the primary source kitchens for hydrocarbon accumulations on the adjacent Laminaria and Flamingo Highs. Interpretation of seismic data suggests that deposition in this part of the Bonaparte Basin commenced in the Permo-Carboniferous. Following a phase of regional compression in the Late Triassic, a succession of fluvio-deltaic clastic rocks was deposited during the Early and Middle Jurassic. The area underwent significant faulting in the Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous in association with rifting and break-up on the northwestern margin of Australia. During this period, subsidence, coupled with rising sea level, established relatively deep water depositional environments. The Late Cretaceous to Paleogene was a period of relative tectonic quiescence as the region responded to post-rift thermal subsidence. Mesozoic rift features were overlain by prograding Cretaceous clastic and Cenozoic carbonate sediments. Late Miocene convergence of the Australian and Eurasian plates resulted in flexural downwarp of the Timor Trough, and widespread reactivation of extensional fault systems within the Bonaparte Basin.
properties.source: Whittam, D.B., Norvick, M.S., McIntyre, C.L., 1996. Mesozoic and Cainozoic tectonostratigraphy of western Zoca and adjacent areas., APPEA Journal 1996

properties.description: The Malita Graben is a Mesozoic to Cainozoic depocentre of the Bonaparte Basin in offshore northern Australia, containing more than 10 km of siliciclastic non-marine and marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Malita Graben is the major part of the elongated northeast-trending graben system subdivided into the Malita and Calder grabens. These graben lie between platform and shelf areas of relatively shallow Precambrian basement covered by Mesozoic and Cainozoic sediments and in some areas by thin late Palaeozoic sediments. The Malita Graben is a depositional trough, bordered by the Sahul Platform to the north and the Darwin Shelf and Petrel Sub-basin to the south. It is bounded on both sides by intersecting east-northeast to northeast trending faults with large displacements. The graben system was initiated during Early Jurassic rifting and was a major depocentre from the Middle Jurassic to the Early Cretaceous. The Middle Jurassic to Lower Cretaceous syn-rift sediments often pinch out to the north on the up-thrown side of the basin bounding fault. Deep crustal seismic data show that the bounding faults are nearly vertical and the depression is fairly symmetrical. It may represent a flexural depression that developed on the inboard part of an upper plate rift margin. Total sediment thickness of the graben is unknown. However, the graben system is estimated to contain over 10 km of late Palaeozoic to Recent sedimentary rocks overlying Precambrian basement. No petroleum discovery has been made in the graben. Exploration to date has tended to focus on the Jurassic and earliest Cretaceous sequences underlying the Bathurst Island Group. These exploration wells were generally located along or near the graben-boundary faults. The Jurassic source rocks are of low quality and overmature in general, and reservoir quality is relatively poor due largely to depth of burial. The Bathurst Island Group (Campanian to Maastrichitian) has generally been considered a regional seal in the graben, and consequently its hydrocarbon potential has largely been ignored. However, some sandstone intervals within the Bathurst Island Group are potential reservoirs.
properties.source: West, B., Passmore, V.L., 1994. Hydrocarbon potential for the Bathurst Island Group, Northeast Bonaparte Basin: implication for future exploration., APEA Journal 34(1)

properties.description: The Beermullah Trough is a northwest-trending depocentre in the Perth Basin containing a series of compressional anticlines and a succession of Mesozoic sedimentary rocks which thickens towards the east.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Mandurah Terrace is a Late Paleozoic to Cenozoic shelf adjacent to the Vlaming Sub-basin that separates the Dandaragan Trough to the north from the Bunbury Trough to the south, and is bound to the east by the Darling Fault.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Early Permian to Recent Abrolhos Sub-basin is a mostly offshore, elongate, NNW-trending rift basin located in the northern Perth Basin and contains at least 7000 m of marine to continental sediments.
properties.overview: The Early Permian to Recent Abrolhos Sub-basin is a NNW-trending rift basin located in the offshore northern Perth Basin. The sub-basin forms part of a complex and extensive poly-phase Permian to Cretaceous rift system along the southwestern Australian margin. 12 exploration wells have been drilled within the sub-basin since 1965 leading to the Dunsborough-1 oil and gas discovery and the Frankland-1 and Perserverance-1 gas discoveries in 2007. The sub-basin overlies the Silurian to Ordovician Tumblagooda Sandstone of the Southern Carnarvon Basin in the north and Proterozoic crystalline basement including the Northampton Complex in the south. Stratigraphic fill in the Abrolhos Sub-basin incorporates a series of Lower Permian to Lower Cretaceous rift-sag successions (6000 m thick) overlain by a thin passive margin cover (up to 850 m thick). However, it is primarily a depocentre for Permian and Triassic strata. The Abrolhos Sub-basin was initiated during Permian rifting when a series of NNW-trending, westerly-downthrown half graben formed and infilled with glacial, marine and continental sediments. Post-rift subsidence during the Late Permian and Early Triassic was associated with the deposition of marine and continental sedimentary rocks. The main depocentre shifted westward into the adjacent Houtman Sub-basin during a Late Triassic and Jurassic rift-sag event, although sediment continued to accumulate in the Abrolhos Sub-basin throughout the Jurassic. The Middle Jurassic to Early Cretaceous break-up of Australia and Greater India produced a complex series of listric-normal faults followed by regional and local uplift and erosion throughout the Abrolhos Sub-basin. Post-break-up deposits have formed a westward thickening passive margin cover of marine clastics and carbonates above the Permian to Lower Cretaceous stacked rift-sag successions. The recent discoveries, a commercial oil discovery at Cliff Head on the ajacent Beagle Ridge, palaeo-oil columns detected in the Cliff Head, Dunsborough, Frankland and Perserverance fields and in dry wells at Flying Foam-1, Hadda-1, Houtman-1, Leander Reef-1, Lilac-1, Livet-1, Mentelle-1, and Morangie-1, along with shows at several stratigraphic levels indicate that much of the Abrolhos Sub-basin has potential for both oil and gas. In particular, there is considerable potential for further discoveries in Permian and Lower Triassic reservoirs sealed by Lower Triassic marine shales (Kockatea Shale), where structural and stratigraphic traps have formed prior to the main period of generation and expulsion from the Abrolhos Sub-basin during the Middle to Late Jurassic.
properties.source: Crostella, A., 2001. Geology and petroleum potential of the Abrolhos Sub-basin, Western Australia, Geological Survey of Western Australia. Report 75

properties.description: The Laminaria High is a Late Paleozoic to Cenozoic platform bordered by the Flamingo Syncline and Nancar Trough in the Bonaparte Basin. It forms part of the Jurassic Elang-Elang Petroleum System and has producing oil fields.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Permian to Cainozoic Turtle Dove Ridge is a north-northwest orientated basement ridge that contains up to 5km of predominantly siliciclastic marine and non-marine sedimentary rocks.
properties.overview: The Turtle Dove Ridge is a north-northwest orientated basement ridge beneath the continental shelf and slope that divides the offshore northern and southern parts of the Perth Basin. The Turtle Dove Ridge extends over an area of 4100 sq. km from shallow coastal waters to 1000 m water depth. Although it is a well established structural element of the Perth Basin, the structural nature of the Turtle Dove Ridge is still poorly understood and is best described as a broad area of shallow basement. The Turtle Dove Ridge formed from the inversion of Permian, Triassic and Jurassic syn-rift and post-rift strata during the break-up of Australia and Antarctica in the Valanginian. Uplift was driven by either deep-seated intrusions and/or transpressional movement on strike-slip faults, and resulted in the erosion of up to 3000 m of stratigraphic section. The Turtle Dove Ridge thus consists of only a relatively thin stratigraphic section (1 to 5 km) in which Permian to Lower Triassic strata underlie the Valanginian break-up unconformity. Known strata include a marine carbonate Cenozoic to Cretaceous section, Middle to Lower Triassic continental sandstones, Lower to Middle Triassic marine shales, and Lower Permian marine shales. The Turtle Dove Ridge is a poorly explored part of the Perth Basin with only one well drilled in 1975, and no significant exploration since the Woodside Beagle Seismic survey in 1992 and Enterprise Oil's Plum Seismic Survey in 1992. Permian and Triassic marine shales form mature source rock intervals and regional seals across the Turtle Dove Ridge. It is uncertain if any reservoir units underlie the marine shales, however if present, these would have low primary porosities due to the original deep burial. The Turtle Dove Ridge contains several large (~100 sq. km) Valanginian- and possible Permian-age structures with fault-dependant closure. However, successful petroleum exploration depends on identifying potential reservoir intervals and areas with favourable timing of hydrocarbon migration versus trap formation.
properties.source: Bradshaw, B.E., Rollet, N., Totterdell, J.M., Borissova, I., 2003. A revised structural framework for frontier basins on the southern and southwestern Australian continental margin., Geoscience Australia. Record 2003/03

properties.description: The Dongara Terrace, located in the northern Perth Basin, forms part of a fault-bounded ridge that separates the Abrolhos Sub-basin and the Dandaragan Trough.
properties.comments: Contains predominantly Carboniferous-Jurassic rocks with a thin Cenozoic cover.
properties.overview: null
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Early Cambrian to Tertiary Petrel Sub-basin occupies the southern part of the Bonaparte Basin in Western Australia and the Northern Territory and contains 15 km of marine and nonmarine siliciclastics and carbonates with minor volcanics.
properties.overview: The Early Cambrian to Tertiary Petrel Sub-basin occupies the southern part of the Bonaparte Basin in Western Australia and the Northern Territory and is a Palaeozoic rift, the boundary faults of which converge to form its southerly termination. The Sub-basin contains up to 15,000 m of marine and nonmarine siliciclastics and carbonates with minor basal volcanics. Deposition commenced during the Early Cambrian with the extrusion of basic volcanics. Subsequent crustal sag allowed deposition of marine, predominantly siliciclastic sediments until the Early Ordovician. Uplift during the Ordovician terminated marine sedimentation. This is probably unconformably overlain by a succession of evaporites of Silurian or Devonian age. NW oriented rifting during the Devonian initiated more widespread sedimentation with deposition of a Late Devonian to Westphalian succession of marine, deltaic and fluvial siliciclastics with minor carbonates. Reactivation of the NW oriented rift led to a short pulse of fluvial sedimentation, followed by Late Carboniferous to Permian sedimentation characterised by a large input of coarse fluvio-glacial siliciclastics followed by deposition of glacial outwash and lacustrine sediments. During the Latest Permian to Early Jurassic, deposition of marine, deltaic and fluvial siliciclastics and carbonates continued until, in the Middle Jurassic, NE trending rifting occurred which led to a period of uplift in the Callovian. Subsequent Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous marine to deltaic siliciclastics onlap this breakup unconformity. A pronounced drop in sealevel during the Valanginian led to erosion over much of the sub-basin. This unconformity is overlain by a condensed sequence of claystone and a thick succession of marine siliciclastics spanning the remainder of the Cretaceous. Progradation to the northwest during the Paleocene and Eocene led to the termination of significant sedimentation in the sub-basin. Proven source rocks occur in the Late Devonian, Carboniferous and Permian with currently no hydrocarbon production, although gas production is planned in the near future. The gas accumulations are contained in inversion structures in Late Triassic reservoirs.
properties.source: McConachie, B.A., Bradshaw, M.T., Bradshaw, J., 1996. Petroleum systems of the Petrel sub-basin - an integrated approach to basin analysis and identification of hydrocarbon exploration opportunities., APPEA Journal 36(1)

properties.description: The offshore, Permian to Recent Ashmore Platform of the Bonaparte Basin contains about 8 km of marine siliciclastics and carbonates, nonmarine siliciclastics and volcanics.
properties.overview: The offshore Permian to Recent Ashmore Platform is an elevated block which lies west of the Vulcan Sub-basin, at the western extremity of the Bonaparte Basin, and adjoins the Browse Basin to the south. It contains about 8,000 m of marine siliciclastics and carbonates, nonmarine siliciclastics and volcanics. A westerly concave fault zone divides the platform into two segments; a western terrain with mainly west dipping faults, and an eastern terrain with both east and west dipping faults. Sedimentation in the area was probably initiated as a result of Late Carboniferous to Early Permian rifting with deposition of a thick succession of shallow marine to fluvio-deltaic sediments during the Permian to Triassic. North-south transpression in the Late Triassic resulted in uplift and erosion. Widespread faulting and uplift commenced in the late Middle Jurassic, concurrent with intracratonic rifting in the adjacent Vulcan Sub-basin, and led to extensive erosion of Jurassic-Triassic strata. Post-rift thermal subsidence in the Valanginian resulted in transgression and the re-commencement of shallow marine deposition on the platform. Subsidence continued through the Cretaceous with the deposition of marine siliciclastics followed by subtropical and tropical carbonates in the Paleogene and Neogene. Sedimentation was interrupted by a major Oligocene hiatus which is recognised throughout the North West Shelf. Only a few wells have been drilled on the Ashmore Platform and exploration has been sporadic, with exploration concentrating on the proven Vulcan Sub-basin. The only hydrocarbon discovery on the platform is the Puffin Field, where oil is reservoired within Late Cretaceous sub-marine fans which extend from the Vulcan Sub-basin onto the southeast margin of the platform. The proven Late Jurassic source rocks of the Vulcan Sub-basin are either absent or thin and immature across the Ashmore Platform. The source potential of the Early Triassic and Early Permian section is largely untested.
properties.source: Hocking, R.M., Mory, A.J., Williams, I.R., 1994. An atlas of Neoproterozoic and Phanerozoic basins of Western Australia, in Purcell, P.G. & Purcell, R.R. (eds), The sedimentary basins of Western Australia. Proceedings of a PESA Symposium, Perth

properties.description: The Bedout Sub-basin is located on Australia's North West Shelf in the southern Roebuck Basin. It contains a Late Paleozoic-Cenozoic succession up to 7 km thick.
properties.overview: The Bedout Sub-basin is an east-northeast to west-southwest-trending Paleozoic-Mesozoic depocentre in the southern Roebuck Basin containing up to 7 km of Paleozoic-Holocene sedimentary rocks. The sub-basin is separated from the Beagle Sub-basin to the west by the North Turtle Hinge Zone, and partly bounded to the northwest by the Bedout High. The Mesozoic succession has generally experienced only mild structuring, and thickens to the west before pinching out against, and partly draping over, the Bedout High. To the east and south the Mesozoic sediments thin and progressively onlap the older Paleozoic succession of the Canning Basin. The Bedout High locally separates the Bedout Sub-basin to the south from the Rowley Sub-basin to the north. The high consists of uplifted and eroded Permo-Carboniferous sedimentary rocks above an interpreted faulted basement core, and is capped by Permian volcanics. Lower to Middle Triassic sediments onlap the feature from all directions and approximately 3 km of Upper Triassic-Holocene sediments are draped over the top. Hydrocarbons have been disovered in the Bedout Sub-basin at the Phoenix 1 and Phoenix South 1 wells.
properties.source: null

properties.description: The Cambrian to Recent Bonaparte Basin is a large, mainly offshore petroleum-producing basin on the northwestern Australian multiple-rifted margin. It contains up to 15 km of marine-fluvial siliciclastic and carbonate sediments.
properties.comments: Highly suitable for CO2 storage (Carbon Storage Taskforce, 2010, Australia's Potential for the Geological Storage of CO2, RET, Canberra)
properties.overview: The Cambrian to Recent Bonaparte Basin is a fan-shaped hydrocarbon-producing basin extending over 329,000 sq. km in offshore and onshore northwestern Australia. It contains up to 15 km of sediments, comprising the southern Palaeozoic and northern Mesozoic depocentres. The basin developed during two phases of Palaeozoic extension and Late Triassic compression prior to the onset of Mesozoic extension. Initial rifting occurred in the Late Devonian (northwest-trending Petrel Sub-basin) and was orthogonally overprinted in the Late Carboniferous to Early Permian by northeast-trending rift basins (proto-Malita and proto-Vulcan depocentres). Regional north-south compression, uplift and erosion in the Late Triassic, together with salt tectonics, produced inversion structures and anticlines in the Petrel Sub-basin. Erosion and collapse of these uplifted areas led to the widespread deposition of Upper Triassic to Middle Jurassic `redbeds' and fluvio-deltaic clastics. Late Jurassic extension resulted in a series of linked, northeast-trending (Vulcan Sub-basin, Malita and Calder Grabens) and southeast-trending (Sahul Syncline) grabens. The Jurassic depocentres contain thick marine mudstones flanked by fan delta sandstones. A thick post-rift Cretaceous to Tertiary succession is dominated by fine-grained clastic and carbonate facies. Late Miocene to Pliocene convergence of the Australian and Eurasian plates resulted in flexural downwarp of the Timor Trough and widespread fault reactivation. The most prospective part of the basin includes the Vulcan Sub-basin, Laminaria-Flamingo High and northern Sahul Platform. The Upper Jurassic marine section is the major source interval in the outboard grabens, together with Middle to Lower Jurassic marine shales and coals. In the Petrel Sub-basin the main sources are postulated Lower Carboniferous marine shales and Permian coals and pro-delta shales. Sandstone reservoirs range in age from Carboniferous to Permian in the Petrel Sub-basin and Londonderry High, Triassic to Cretaceous in the Vulcan Sub-basin, and Jurassic in the northern parts of the basin. Fault seal breach is one of the main risks in the western part of the basin.
properties.source: Mory, A.J., 1991. Geology of the offshore Bonaparte Basin, northwestern Australia., Geological Survey of Western Australia. Report 29

properties.description: The Palaeozoic to Cainozoic Barrow Sub-basin is an oil- and gas-producing offshore basin on the northwest Australian margin, which contains over 10 km of predominantly Mesozoic clastic deltaic and marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Palaeozoic to Cainozoic Barrow Sub-basin is an elongate, north-northeast to south-southwest trending offshore basin (0 to 200 m water depth), which forms part of the Northern Carnarvon Basin on Australia's Northwest Shelf. Since exploration commenced in 1954, 77 fields have been discovered (December 2002) including the giant Barrow Island oil field. The Barrow Sub-basin is a deep synclinal graben that forms a depocentre for over 10 km of predominantly Mesozoic to Cainozoic strata, which is flanked to the east and west by shallower faulted terraces that contain up to 5 km of Palaeozoic to Cainozoic strata. Basin development commenced in the Palaeozoic, but the present-day structural setting is largely a result of  Late Triassic to Early Jurassic rifting between Australia and Greater India/Western Burma Block. Subsequent extension events in the Middle to Late Jurassic and Early Cretaceous, Late Cretaceous inversion and Miocene compression produced many of the structural traps within the Barrow Sub-basin. Deposition of fluvial-deltaic and marginal marine sandstones during the Late Triassic to Early Jurassic was followed by a transgressive phase of clastic marine sedimentation in the Early to Late Jurassic. The commercially important Barrow Delta prograded northwards across much of the Barrow Sub-basin during the Early Cretaceous, and was followed by a transgressive phase of clastic marine sedimentation until the mid-Cretaceous. Progradation of carbonate wedges dominated deposition during the mid-Cretaceous to Cainozoic. The main exploration plays in the Barrow Sub-basin comprise anticlinal and faulted structures, with the regional seal formed by Lower Cretaceous deep marine shales. Oil accumulations occur predominantly in Lower Cretaceous reservoirs, with some also found in Upper Triassic and Jurassic reservoirs. Gas accumulations occur predominantly in Upper Triassic, Jurassic, and Lower Cretaceous reservoir intervals. Most oil and gas accumulations were sourced from Upper Jurassic marine shales, with some evidence for contributions from other source intervals. The main pulse of hydrocarbon generation from Upper Jurassic source rocks occurred during the Early Cretaceous, and continued throughout the Late Cretaceous to Cainozoic.
properties.source: Baillie, P.W., Jacobson, E.P., 1997. Prospectivity and exploration history of the Barrow Sub-basin, Western Australia., APPEA Journal 37(1)

properties.description: The Carboniferous to Recent Beagle Sub-basin covers an area of 30 000 sq. km in water depths up to 2000m and is located in the Northern Carnarvon Basin. The area is relatively unexplored with only 17 wells (by 2001) and one oil discovery (Nebo).
properties.overview: The Carboniferous to Recent Beagle Sub-basin covers an area of 30 000 sq. km in water depths up to approximately 2000m and is located in the Northern Carnarvon Basin. The sub-basin trends northeasterly and is characterised by a series of north-trending, Triassic to Jurassic faults blocks, separated by intervening structural lows. These structures formed in response to the break-up of eastern Gondwana in the Early Jurassic, with the formation of the Carnarvon Basin occurring from the Palaeozoic onwards. The Beagle sub-basin structure contains over 10km of Palaeozoic and Cainozoic sediments in the principal depocentres of the Cossigny and Beagle troughs. Pre-rift sequences (Triassic to mid-Pleinsbachian) are composed of marine and fluvio-deltaic sediments. The syn-rift phase (mid-Pliensbachian to mid-Valanginian), during which the sub-basin formed, is composed of deltaic to restricted marine sediments. The post-rift (mid Valanginian to mid-Santonian) to passive margin phase (mid-Santonian to Miocene) is composed of transgressive shaly marine sediments to a variety of marine carbonate sediments deposited in open marine shelfal environments. The area is relatively unexplored with only 17 wells drilled by 2001. Several of the wells tested structural traps but failed due to trap breach. There is one field discovery (Nebo) containing 5 million barrels of recoverable oil. There is further petroleum potential with Mesozoic sequences thickening from the basin margin fault system to the northeast-trending Cossigny Trough. Triassic and Jurassic source rocks are mature for oil generation, as indicated by vitrinite reflectance. The central deep area of the trough is likely to have been within the oil generation window during much of the Tertiary. Favourable structural configurations have existed for long-distance migration toward the De Grey Nose from the Cossigny Trough within the Beagle Sub-basin and from the Dampier Sub-basin.
properties.source: Blevin, J.E., Stephenson, A.E., 1994. Mesozoic structural development of the Beagle Sub-basin - implications for the petroleum potential of the northern Carnarvon Basin., in Purcell, P.G. & Purcell, R.R. (eds), The sedimentary basins of Western Australi*

properties.description: The Late Carboniferous to Recent Dampier Sub-basin is an elongate, northeast-southwest trending depositional complex within the Northern Carnarvon Basin and contains over 10 km of marine and non-marine sediments.
properties.overview: The Late Carboniferous to Recent Dampier Sub-basin is an elongate, northeast-southwest trending depositional complex within the Northern Carnarvon Basin. The basin contains four main structural entities (Kendrew Trough, Madeleine Trend, Lewis Trough and Legendre Trend) that appear to have originated during the Late Triassic and Early Jurassic in response to the final stages of Australia-Greater India breakup. The Lewis Trough is the principle depocentre of the Dampier Sub-basin and contains more than 10 km of marine and non-marine sediment. Extensive exploration has been conducted over the basin with many discoveries including the Legendre, Wanaea, and Cossack oil fields. Triassic sedimentation was initially dominated by a regional marine transgression and was followed by regressive fluvio-deltaic sequences deposited during the Middle to Late Triassic. Deposition of Early Jurassic-age sediments represents the first phase of syn-rift sedimentation. The Dampier Sub-basin was largely bypassed by sedimentation during the Early Cretaceous because of its distal location from the Barrow Delta. The break-up between Australia and Greater India marks the end of syn-rift deposition and is represented by an intra-Valanginian unconformity. After the breakup of Gondwana, changed oceanic circulation patterns and sediment supply created a basin-wide change from siliciclastic to calcareous deposition that has since dominated, forming prograding wedges that are up to several kilometres thick. The source rocks of the Dampier Sub-basin include the Jurassic Athol Formation and the Dingo Claystone. The reservoir units include the Jurassic Legendre and Angel Formations and the Lower Cretaceous Birdrong Sandstone. In addition to the regional Lower Cretaceous Muderong Shale, intraformational seals are also present. Traps include uplifted horst blocks, rollover anticlines, stratigraphic pinchouts, incised valley/channel deposits and basin floor fans. Hydrocarbon migration is predominantly from the deep Jurassic Lewis Trough.
properties.source: Kopsen, E., McGann, G., 1985. A review of the hydrocarbon habitat of the Eastern and central Barrow-Dampier sub-basin, Western Australia, APEA Journal 25(1)

properties.description: The Early Carboniferous to Holocene Browse Basin is a large, offshore hydrocarbon-proven basin on the northwestern Australian poly-phased margin containing more than 15 km of siliciclastic non-marine and marine rocks.
properties.overview: The Early Carboniferous to Holocene Browse Basin is a large, offshore basin on the northwestern Australian poly-phased margin. The basin is a proven hydrocarbon province, with major undeveloped gas/condensate fields in the outer and central basin, and minor oil discoveries on the basin's eastern margin. The Browse Basin developed during six major tectonic phases: Late Carboniferous to Early Permian extension; Late Permian to Triassic thermal subsidence; Late Triassic to Early Jurassic inversion; Early to Middle Jurassic extension; Late Jurassic to mid-Tertiary thermal subsidence; and Late Miocene inversion. Initial extension resulted in half-graben geometries and the formation of two distinct depocentres, the Caswell and Barcoo sub-basins. These depocentres contain in excess of 15 km sedimentary section, and lie in 100 to 1800 m water depth. The outer Browse Basin comprises the deep-water Scott Plateau (1500 to 5000 m water depth) and Seringapatam Sub-basin. The Carboniferous section is predominantly fluvio-deltaic, and the Permian to Lower Triassic section is mostly marine. Middle to Upper Triassic rocks include fluvial and shallow marine clastics and minor carbonates. Lower to Middle Jurassic syn-rift sediments comprise deltaic and coastal-plain clastics and coal. Widespread erosion occurred in the Callovian, with onlapping Upper Jurassic sandstones and shales providing a thin regional seal across most pre-Callovian structures. Widespread transgression commenced in the Valanginian and peaked in the Turonian, and resulted in the deposition of thick open marine claystones. The Turonian to Cenozoic section records a major progradational clastic-to-carbonate cycle. The Lower Cretaceous claystones provide a thick regional seal and contain potential oil-prone source rocks. Potential source rocks also occur in the Upper Jurassic, Middle to Lower Jurassic, Triassic and syn-rift Palaeozoic sections. Reservoir facies are best developed in sandstones of the fluvio-deltaic Middle to Lower Jurassic section, and in Cretaceous submarine fans of Berriasian, Barremian, Campanian and Maastrichtian age.
properties.source: Blevin, J.E., Struckmeyer, H.I.M., Cathro, D.L., Totterdell, J.M., Boreham, C.J., Romine, K.K., Loutit, T.S., Sayers, J., 1998. Tectonostratigraphic framework and petroleum systems of the Browse Basin North West Shelf., in Purcell, P.G. & Purcell, R.R. *
